This code also performs some simple cleaning with standard preprocess from gensim_utilities

Gensim.utils.simple.preprocess : 'Convert a document into a list of lowercase tokens, ignoring tokens that are too short or too long'.

In [7]:
book_corpus = []
for book_filename in book_filenames:
    with codecs.open(book_filename, "r", "utf-8") as book_file:
        book_corpus.append(
            gensim.models.doc2vec.TaggedDocument(
                gensim.utils.simple_preprocess( # Cleans text with simple_preprocess
                    book_file.read()),
                    ["{}".format(book_filename)])) # Tags each book with its filename

Code snippets for different cleaning purposes¶

Sentence_to_wordlist removes irrelevant characters and splits into words (not tokens)¶

In [112]:
wordlist=[]
def sentence_to_wordlist(inputw):
    clean = re.sub("[^a-zA-Z]"," ", input.lower())
    wordlist = clean.split()
    return wordlist

The cleanlist version cleans the text, returns sentences, not words¶

In [182]:
cleanlist=[]
clean_sentence=[]
def sentence_to_cleanlist(input):
    clean = re.sub("[^a-zA-Z]"," ", input.lower())
    wordlist = clean.split()
    clean_sentence.append(wordlist)
    return clean_sentence

make_fin_sent creates final sentences without stopwords, to be used for the topic extraction part later¶

In [114]:
#def remove_stopword_sentences(sentences):

def make_fin_sent(sent_in):
    fin_sent=[]
    for sent in sent_in:
        fin_sent.append(remove_stopwords(sent))
    return fin_sent

remove_stopwords removes all english stopwords, one code for a single sentence, one for looping of sentences¶

In [122]:
def remove_stopwords(words):
       return [word for word in words if word not in stop_words]
In [ ]:
sent_unstop=[]
def remove_stopwords_sentence(sents):
    for sent in sents:
        sent_unstop.append(remove_stopwords(sent))
    return sent_unstop

Packing a normalization code (tokenize, lemmatize, stem , lowercase)¶

In [87]:
norm_sents=[]
def normalize_sentences(sentence_in):
    norm_sent=[]
    for sentence in sentence_in:
        for token in nltk.tokenize.word_tokenize(sentence):
            if token not in stop_words:
               # print(token)
                token= lem.lemmatize(token).lower()
               # print(token)
                token= stem.stem(token)
               # print(token)
                norm_sents.append(token)
                print(norm_sents)
    return norm_sents

Plot a limited region with points¶

In [396]:
def plot_region(x_bounds, y_bounds):
    
    slice = points[(x_bounds[0] <= points.x) & (points.x <= x_bounds[1]) & 
                   (y_bounds[0] <= points.y) & (points.y <= y_bounds[1])]
    
    ax = slice.plot.scatter("x", "y", s=35, figsize=(10, 6))
    for i, point in slice.iterrows():
        ax.text(point.x + 0.005, point.y + 0.005, point.word, fontsize=11)

Find 'word pairs' completing a shown relationship.¶

In [408]:
def nearest_similarity_cosmul(start1, end1, start2):
    
    similarities = word_model.wv.most_similar_cosmul(
        positive=[start1, start2],
        negative=[end1])
    end2 = similarities[0][0]
    print("{start1} is related to {end1}, as {start2} is related to {end2}".format(**locals()))
    return end2
